## Platform Rules

### Twitter / X  (≤280 characters total)

- Lead with a bold claim, surprising stat, or provocative question.
- Reserve ~23 chars for the article URL placeholder `{url}`.
- No hashtags in the main tweet (they eat characters; use in replies if needed).
- If the idea cannot fit in 280 chars, propose a thread: first tweet hooks,
  subsequent tweets expand, last tweet includes the URL.
- Character count includes spaces and punctuation.

### LinkedIn  (150–300 characters for the body + up to 3 hashtags)

- Professional but personal.  "I" and "we" are acceptable.
- Open with a one-sentence insight or lesson, not a question.
- End with a sentence that teases what the full article reveals.
- Hashtags: lowercase, no spaces, directly relevant to topic and industry.
- Do NOT include the URL in the body text — LinkedIn preview card handles it.

### Instagram  (≤2200 characters caption + ≤30 hashtags)

- First line must stand alone as a hook (appears before "...more" cut-off).
- Emojis are welcome — use 1-3 thematically relevant ones per paragraph break.
- Tell a micro-story or pose a relatable scenario before moving to the insight.
- End the caption with a soft CTA ("Link in bio for the full guide.").
- Separate hashtag block from caption with five line breaks.
- Hashtags: mix high-volume (≥1M posts), mid-volume (100K-1M), and niche (≤100K).

### TikTok Hook  (≤150 characters — first spoken words of a video script)

- Hook fires in the first 3 words.  Pattern-interrupt types:
    question    — "Why do most marketers...?"
    controversy — "Unpopular opinion: long-form is dead."
    statistic   — "83% of readers never scroll past..."
    personal_story — "I spent 6 months writing content nobody read until..."
- No hashtags — this is a spoken hook, not a caption.
- The hook should make a viewer stop scrolling in ≤3 seconds.

### Threads  (≤500 characters)

- Conversational.  Write as if posting a shower thought or hot take.
- Frame as an opinion, observation, or open question to invite replies.
- One idea only — no sub-points.
- Contractions and informal language are expected.
- No hashtags.

## Output Constraints

- Produce only the SocialSnippets JSON object.
- Validate all character counts before outputting.
- Do not include markdown fences or commentary outside the JSON.
- URL placeholders use the literal string `{url}` — do not invent URLs.
